The biggest user problem I've run across since the death of wiki markup in Confluence is that it is now just as easy to make a link via a URL as a page name, and for naive users who don't know much about wikis it is, in fact, easier and more obvious to use the URL.  It also is harder to detect this, since a URL link and a correct page link look exactly the same.

Add a feature where, when the user puts in a link to a page as a URL link, the link is re-written to a page link (perhaps with an option to override) or the user is at least warned. It shouldn't be too hard to detect when the base URL points back into the wiki.

Other options would include making URL links look different from page links in some way, or a tool that audits links and detects when pages have these bad links and allows them to be fixed from a central location.

